{"/service/ndnp/ndhi/batch_ndhi_kensal_ver01/data/sn89074274/00212475932/1921021001/0057.xml":{"full_text":"/'AGE EIGHT\nFrom Wednesday's Daily\nThe interior of the Right Price\nstore is being repainted at the pres\nent time.\nC. 0. Langer, the Sanborn merchant,\nwas looking after business matters in\nthe city last night.\nMrs. Vernon Gale entertained Miss\nEmma DeWitt and Clara L. Larson\nat dinner Monday.\nAttorney C. S. Buck, of Jamestown,\nN. D., was looking after legal busi\nness in the city last night.\nToday marks the beginning of the\nLenten season. Today is known as\nAsh Wednesday.\nMr. and Mrs. Bob Rathje of Tower\nCity were in the city Tuesday and\nremained over to attend the organ\nrecital at the Congregational church.\nHerb. Weston arrived in the city\nthis morning from the farm near\nSheldon and will spend a few days in\nthe city.\nHerman Cook and his mother, who\nhave been at Long Beach, California,\nfor the past month or two, returned\nto Valley City Monday of this week.\nA. McPaul, wire chief of the local\ntelephone exchange, will go to Fargo\nthis evening to attend a meeting of\nthe company.\nA few automobile drivers in the\ncity have secured the 1921 licenses.\nThe licenses have a blue background\nand white numerals.\nKermit R. Siegfried, 13 years old:\nson of Mr. and Mrs. W. A. Siegfried\nof Sanborn, N. D., died at a Fargo hos\npital yesterday. Interment will be\nmade in a Fargo cemetery.\nFriday afternoon twelve ladies were\n4entertained\nby Mrs. C. Calhoun in\nhonor of her daughter, Mrs. Yule.\nLuncheon was served and the after\nnoon spent in a social manner.\nA surprise party was given at the\nhome of Mrs. Phil Schoefter Monday\nin honor of Mrs. Schoefter's birthday.\nThe evening was spent in dancing and\nsinging and a very delicious lunch\nwas served.\nThe rumor is current on the streets\nthat Miss Chapman, one of the teach-1\ners in our public schools was recently\nmarried in St. Paul to a Mr. Arthur\nHill. We are giving the item for\nwhat it is worth and have reason to\nbelieve that it is correct.\nH. Nelson, 64 years old, farmer liv\ning at Fingal, N. D., died at a Fargo\nhospital Monday of heart trouble. He\nhad been ill for 10 days. The body\nwill be sent to Nome, N. D., for bur\nial. Mr. Nelson is survived by his\nwidow,*one son and one daughter.\nMrs. Fred Spiker entertained the\nDegree of Honor officers at her home\nMonday evening. Curios and famous\npaintings were enjoyed by the guests.\nMrs. Anna Meinhardt was given first\nprize for having the 'most paintings.\nand Mollie Tullius, the consolation1\ngift. Delicious refreshments were\n6erved.\nH. F. Arnold was here from Fargo\nyesterday looking after the interests\nof the I. V. A. an this community, try\ning to get the local unit going. A\nstate convention is to be held at Grand\nForks this coming Friday at which\ntime the keynote of the coming cam\npaign will no doubt be put forth.\nLouis Gillette, the popular Upper\nFifth avenue shoe hospital proprietor,!\nleft this afternoon for Fargo, where\nhe goes to purchase a large stock\nof leather and other goods for his\nshop. Mr. Gillette is a hustler and is\npreparing for a big business the com\ning season.\nMiss Emma DeWitt, who has been\nhome demonstration agent for Barnes\ncounty for some time, left last night\nfor Danville, 111., where she goes to a\nmore lucrative position. Miss DeWitt\nhas made many friends here who will\nwish her much success at Danville.\nThere will be no successor to take her\nplace.\nL. Sachs, the genial proprietor of\nthe Family Shoe Store opposite the\nGrand theater, has recently put in a\nnew and complete line of ladies and\ngentlemen's shoes, and is now busy\ndisplaying the same in his place of\nbusiness. Mr. Sachs is pother live\nyoung business man who believes in\nkeeping abreast of the times.\nClarence Eddy, of Chicago, Uhe not\ned pipe organist, gave a very fine\norgan recital in the Congregational\nchurch Tuesday evening to a fair\nsized but appreciative audience. Mr.\nEddy demonstrated that he knew how\nto handle the pipe organ and that his\nreputation was sustained by the con\ncert he gave last night.\nOne of the neatest and most tasty\ndisplays we have seen yet is in the\nnew quarters of the Sanitary Plumb\ning Heating Co. Mr. Saindon has\nfixed lip his new location in fine shape\nand has a very tasty display of plumb\ning and heating that would do credit'\nto a larger place. Paul Baarstad has\nalso a neat display of electrical goods,\nha\\png his office in the same building.\nIt is with deep regret that the many\nfriends of Mr. and Mrs. W. A. Seig-,\nfried, of Sanborn, learn of the death-'\nof their thirteen year old son, whose\ndemise occurred in one of the Fargo\nhospitals recently- We have been unr\nable at this time to find out the cause\nof the boy's death. We-hereby extend\nour sincere sympathy to Mr. and Mrs.\nSeigfried and family.\nThe seventh annual North Dakota\nchecker tournament is to be held at\nWilKston, N. D., February 22 and\n23. _A large silver cup as well as sev\neral other prizes\"will_be given for the\ncessful piarers. There are sev\neral fellow/ in Valley City who\nV-\nthink they can\nne\nCutcheon toudh.\nplay checkers and\nere is a good chance for them to go\nto Willist'on and find out how much\nthey don't know about checkers.\nThe Home Economics Club held a\nvery pleasant meeting at the home\nof Mrs. C. E. Burgess Monday eve-^\nning, Feb. 7. Roll call was responded\nto with quotations from Lincoln. Miss\nClara Larson gave an interesting ac\ncount of the Boys and Girls Club work\nin Barnes county. This is a great\nwork and one about which people in\ngeneral should be better informed.\nThe remainder of the evening was\nspent in a social manner followed by\na dainty lunch.\nEugene O'Brien, appearing in the\nSelznick picture, \"A Fool and His\nMoney,\" adapted from George Barr\nMcCutcheon's story of the same name,\nI will be 'the attraction at the Grand\ntheater tonight. O'Brien appears in,\nthe role of an American \"best-selling\"\nauthor who goes to the Swiss Tyrol\nfor \"atmosphere\" for his new novel.\niHe buys an ancient castle, and pres\nently goes through more interesting\nexperiences himself than he had\n!counted on for even the hero of his\ncoming novel. There are ghosts and\nalluring women and villainous nobler\nmen, and an admixture of comedy,\nromance and exciting adventure, pre\nsented with the glamourous Mc-\nHarold Coop, son of Mr. and Mrs.\nWalter Coop of this city, is another\nValley City boy who is making good in\nathletics in school circles. Harold\nwas a graduate of the local High\nSchool about 1916, and it was here\nthat he first attracted attention as a\nbasketball and football artist, playing\nremarkably good games of both. He\nalso played on the Grand Forks Um\nversity team in 1917, one of the best\nteams turned out by the University up\nto that time. When he played on the\nlocal High School team, the team was\nfor the first time in history runner up\nin the state tournament, playing in the\nfinal game but being defeated by Mi\nnot. He is now playing with the Uni\nversity of California team at Berkely,\nCalifornia, and is attracting press\ncomment all over that state. In a\ngame with the Oregon Aggies at\nBerkely, Cal., the press of that city\nsays: \"As we had predicted last night\nCoop, the Bruin forward, was the star\nof the contest. Coop proved a sur\nprise to jthfe average spectator by\ndropping in nine consecutixe free\nthrows out of \"eleven attempts. This\nis the best performance turned out by\nany Californian to date.\"\nFrom Monday's Daily\nMrs. Charles Froemke and daughter.\nEleanor, of Marion. N. D\u201e are visiting\nat the home of Mr. and Mrs. O. F.\nEmbert3on of this city.\nPresident James Grady, of the Se\ncurity National Bank, was here Sun\nday and left again last night for Far\ngo.\nW. A. Matson, of the Northern Pa\ncific freight department, was a Val\nley City visitor today, looking after\nthe interests of his company.\nMrs. R. L. Zalk, wife of R. L. Zalk,\nadvertising manager of the Peoples\nOpinion, left yesterday \u00a3or the Twin\nCities where she will spend some time\nvisiting with friends and relatives.\nC. S. Brown and wife, of Rogers, N.\nD., were Valley City visitors last\nnight. Mrs. Brown has just recently\nreturned from an extended visit-with\nher parents at Aberdeen S. D.\nMrs. Ferd Olson, and two Aildren\nof Revere, N. D., are in the city. /The\ndaughter, Macile, was operated upon\nat the Medical Block. Mrs. Olson and\nthe son are guests at the O. F. Em\nbertson home.\nOrville Mason, son of O. H. Mason,\nmake-up on the Times-Record, re\nturned last evening from Grand Forks\nwhere he had been since Friday vis\niting with relatives and friends.\nThe thermometer is hovering around\nsix below today, but it is bright and\nsunny, so that the temperature is just\na reasonable North Dakota life giving\nkind that builds up health.\nThere is one thing that North Dako\nto is getting lots of real gQod advertis\ning about and that is our big potatoes.\nOn all Northern Pacific dining cars\nthey serve great big baked potatoes\nadvertised as North Dakota's Pride\nand they are real big ones ,we will say.\nThe first series of municipal con\ncerts to be giyen by the city was en\njoyed by a large crowd at the. Normal\nAuditorium Sunday afternoon. The\nprogram rendered was much enjoyed\nbeing well carried out by^ those par\nticipating.\nMesdames Kenneth and Eugene Mc\nFarland entertained Saturday after\nnoon at Mrs. Kenneth's home, at six\ntables of six handed euchre. Mrs. C.\nF. Cobb won first prize and Mrs. C. E.\nJohnson the consolation gift. A delic\nious supper was served, following the\ngames.\nJohn D. Gray, secretary of the Val\nley City Fibre Co., left yesterday for\nthe Twin Cities, Chicago, and other\npoints to look over the tow situation,\nanil determine if possible the business\noutlook for the tow manufacturing\nconcerns of the country during tjie\ncoming year.\nLee Cowell left Friday r.ight for\nMinneapolis where he will take a little\nvacation from business cares and visit\nthe big auto show as well as any other\nold show that might be running. He\nis looking after some business matters\nwhile down there and will not return\nhome until the latter part of the week.\nI\n4\nRevenue Collector E. H. Mattingly\nwill visit Valley City February 21 to\n24 for the purpose .of giving informa\ntion to anyone needing it in regard to\nmaking out their income tax report.\nBear these dates in mind and see Mr.\nMattingly when he comes to town if decided on. :.v\nyou are in need of any information.\nB. V. Fowler, one of the oldest tray\neling men on the road, in number of\nyears in service, was here Saturday\nlooking ofter his customers. B. U.\nadmits that he is in big business and\nis engaged in \"squeezing\" both old and\nyoung, lean and fat, he does not care\nwho, so long as he gets the business.\nHe is selling corsets.\nThe state meeting of Modern Wood\nmen of America lodges of North Da\nkota will be held in Valley City on\nMay 4, of this year. North Dakota\nis well up in the list of states having\na large number of camps. North Da\nkota is well up in the list of states\nhaving a large number of camps.\nNorth Dakota has 322 camps. ,7V!\nMrs. C. L. Peterson left on Satur\nday night on No. 4 for the twin cities\nwhere she will join her husband. .Char\nley has been down in Chicago the past\ntwo weeks and other points purchasing\na fine lot of dry goods, ready-to-wear\ngoods and novelties for the Right\nPrice Mercantile Company, and when\nhe gets these new goods in will have\nsome real bargains to offer to the\ntrade.\nheadquarters at Valley City. Mrs.\nCheney will return here about April\nfirst and then these good people will\nagain establish a home here. Their\nmany friends will indeed be pleased\nto hear that they have decided to re\nturn to this city to live.\nThe interior of the Peoples Store is\nbeing remodeled and made more handy\nby the good work of Harvey Taylor\nand the assistance of Contractor Phil\nSchoefter and a crew of carpentersi\nThe office has been placed upstairs\nin the northwest corner much enlarged\nand improved, making a very light and\nattractive office with lots of space to\nwork in. Downstairs and in the base\nment other improvements are. to be\nmade to take care of other depart\nments to be installed, and when all\nthis have been accomplished the Peo\nples Store will be one of the best and\nsylvania, left by the late Colonel Jacob\nBaker. Among the persons mention-\nFrom Thursday Daily\nNo. 1 on the High Line, was over\nsix hours late this morning.\nH. L. Wright of Leal looked after\nbusiness matters in the city yesterday.\nC. S. Treaster of Leal is looking aft\ner business matters in the city today.\nMartin Gjesvold of Nome, N. D.\nwas here yesterday.\nBenjafhin Norell of Leal, N. D., was\na Valley City visitor last evening. Mr.\n.Norell is Soo agent at Leal.\nJ. Pierce Wolfer, of Moorhead.\nMinn., who is engaged in the insur\nance and real estate business in that\nstate, was in the city last evening\nleaving this morning.\nWork on the High School annual is\nprogressing nicely, according the The\nOwl, the High Sclbol publication. A\nname for the annual has not been\nMrs. A. C. Olsen and Albert Olsen\nmother and brother of C. A. Olsen, of\nthe Valley City Furniture Company,\nspent last week visiting the Olsen\nfamily in this city. Mrs. Olsen re- Lo^s in the fire which destroyed the\nturned_ Saturday to Fargo where she three story Wallace bTock, one of\nis making her home with her daughter,\nMrs. A. T. Strandness and Mr. Albert\nOlsen returned the same day to Ferry\nville, Wis., his home.\nAbe Stern, president of the Stern\nCandy Co., left for the Twitf Cities\nyesterday to attend a meeting of the Michigan, Oregon and Wiscons n.\nMidland Zone National Candy Manu\nfacturer's association, composing the\nstates of Illinois, South Dakota,\nMinnesota, Iowa and North Dakota.\nThis meeting is being held by candy,\nmanufacturers to discuss the business\noutlook for 1921. Mr. Stern, while in\nthe cities, will perhaps purchase some\nnew machinery to be installed in the\nStern Candy Co., manufacturing de\npartment.\nIt has been some time since anybody\nwas around selling rabbit stock ori\nanything of that sort, so Fred Burle\nson, one of our shrewd taxi drivers\nthinkS it is about time to get busy get\nting some of the people's money in\nan easy manner. He has figured it\nout that a turtle ranch Would be a pay\ning investment and has decided to\nstart one on the Benson farm south of\ntown. He is getting ready to sell\nstock in his turtle company and we\nhope bur folks who are in the habit\nof investing in any old thing that\nsounds good will buy liberally. Tur\ntles take years to grow to any size\nand the dividends will be slow in com\ning, all you have to do is to invest\nand then wait with patience for the\nturtles to breed and grow.\n\\f.:\nRev. G. LeRoy White of Jamestown\nN. D., was a guest of Rev. J. S. Wilds\nat the local E, Parsonage yester\nday Rev. Whit# is pastor of the Ep\nworth M. E. church at Jamestown.\nJamestown's landmarks, is estimated\nat more than $100,000. The structure\nwas erected 40 years ago. One of the\nfalling walls crashed through the roof\nof a garage, carrying the roof into\nthe basement.\nMrs. Hugh McDonald left last Sat\nurday evening for Kansas City, where\nshe will join Mr. McDonald who has\nbeen visiting his daughter, Mrs. Koff\nman, for the past three weeks or more.\nAfter a short visit there the McDon\nalds will go on to Biloxi for the bal\nance of the winter.\nThe politeness contest conducted at\nthe High School is too close for com\nfort. The faculty are all determined\nto get a chew of Wrigley's offered as\na prize, and have been going somewhat\nout of the way, it is said, in attempt\ning to show the\nThe total enrollment of 999 for the\nyear at the Agricultural College at\nFargo is remarkably* well distributed\nover the entire state of North Dako\nta, is the statement of Registrar A. H.\nParrott, who has just completed a\nB. L. Cheney recently returned to\nthe city from Michigan, where he had\nbeen spending part of the winter with\nthe5' Au'tman^Taylor^f thre.hine .''\"dyotthe g\u00ab\u00abr^hie.I^riboUon\nmachinery in this stale this year with.\nJamestown is after a wireless sta\ntion, tooth ar^J nail and is doing its\nbest to interest citizens to donate a\nlittle money toward the construction\nof one. The absence of Russell Pray's\n\u2022wireless station in Valley City has\ngiven Jamestown the opportunity to\nbuild a first class Ration, and they\nwill perhaps get it, being directly\nwest of Valley City, and especially\ninvited to get into the radio league.\nIn referring to the Dakota Division of\nthe American Radio Relay League.\nMr. Boyd Phelph, the manager says\nin the January issue of QST: \"We\nmiss the spark of Mr. Pray's station.\n9ix, formerly at Valley City, and it is\na great hardship to have him drop\nout. 7IM has also left for California.\nThese two stations were the ones that\ncompleted the missing link in this\nmost complete department stores in1 route, and it will be hard to find\nthe state. 1 their equal as there are not nearly\nas many good ones to choose from in\nIn Saturday's issue of the Times-, this part of the country as compared\nRecord we carried a telegraph story to other divisions.\"\nunder a Fargo date saying that several Postmaster W. W. Smith advises us\nNorth Dakota people among 400 oth-jthat the campaign inaugurated s'ome\ner heirs were entitled to a share in a. time ago to \"have your mail address\n^800,000,000 estate in Ohio and Penn-\nwho is now on a farm near Velva. The\nland originally given to Col. Baker\nfcr services in the Revolutionary and\n1812 wars, grew immensely valuable\nwhen the town of Chillcothe was lo\ncated on the 5,000 acre tract in Ohio,\nand Philadelphia expanded over 600\nacres of the grant. A long time lease\nhas expired and heirs are endeavoring\nto sell the land. The many friends\nof the Jacobsons hope that they will\nsoon bet a big slice of that huge for\ntune.\ned\nto Street and Number or Lock Box\"\nas the case may be, has resulted in a\nmarked increase in correctly address\u00ad\ned as a beneficiary in this immense. ed letters, received at the local office,\nestate is Mrs. Edwin Jacobson, for- with the result that delivery of same\nmerly of''this city, and the wife of: is greatly expedited. Mr. Smith how\nEdwin Jacobson, who was a former ever reports that there still is room\nemployee of the Times-Record and for improvement as many patrons of\nthe office still receive their mail ad\ndressed simply ''Valley City, N.- D.\"\nwith neither street, number, or box\nnumber and it is needless to say that\n'as there are many people of the same\nname in Valley City, the question\narises: \"Who should have the first shot\nat this one?\" By having your cor\nrespondent place the street and num\nber, or box number as the case may\nbe, on your letters and all mail you\nexpect, there is practically no chance\nfor delays, or its going astray. Help\nout the post office service by making\nan effort to do this\u2014it costs you\nnothing and helps a lot.\nJoseph Brady, who passed away Fri\nday morning, being a member of\nthe Jamestown Lodge No. 995\nB. P. O. Elks, that lodge took charge\nof the remains, which were taken to\nthat city last Sunday. The ibody lay in\nstate at the ElJcs hall until Monday\nmorning, when it was taken tr- Edge\nley, where burial took place. Monday\nafternoon. Mr. Brady had been an in\nvalid for several months, due it is re\nported, to an automobile injury, which\nparalyzed his lower limbs. Prior to\nhis accident he conducted a pool hall\nat Valley. City, where he lived about\nthree years. Previous to that time he\nresided at Edgeley. The deceased is\nsurvived by his widow and two young\ndaughters. The remains were met at\nthe N. P. station at Jamestown -Sun\nday, evening by members of No. 995.\nwho rendered every service possible to\nthe family, and Loren Young accom\npanied them,to Edgeley. Mr. Bnady\nwas also a member of the Knights of\nColumbus of Fargo and Elks and K.\nof C's were pallbearers, being Messrs.\nGeorge Burgett. Matt McGlone. Geo.\nFlynn. Paul Harless, A. J. Rulon and\nWin. Mason. Xi \"J\nftlK WEEKLY TIMCS-RICQBP, VALLEY CITY, NOWTH THURSDAY. FEBRUARY 10, 1921\n\u2014Us\u2014\ngreatest\ndegree of\npoliteness. The judges of the contest\nare hoping that the faculty will drop\nback to their natural ways, so that a\nfair choice can be made. Some\nchanges in rules were also found to\nbe necessary, ^.s the contest is very\nclose, second and third prizes will also\nbe awarded. Second best will receive a\nchew of Black Jack and third pHze\nis a half stick of Yucatan.\nC0S\ntoS 37\nbeing the second largest number from\nany one county attending the college.\nCass county, in which the college is\nlocated, leads with 237 students, and\nBarnes county is next. Eight other\nstates send 121 students, while Can\nada sends one. The eight states are\nMinnesota with 90 South Dakota and\nMontana with 10 each Illinois, Iowa,\nMrs. Frank White addressed a good\nly audience of the League of Women\nVoters at the Commercial Club Rooms\nlast Monday afternoon on the subject\n\"Processes of Law Making.\" Mrs.\nWhite's broad experience in haying at\ntended many past sessions of the leg\nislature and as the wife of ex-Gover\nnor White admirably fits her to ren\nder instruction along these lines.\nMuch interest was shown by the wom\nen present and many questions were\nasked. Through the courtesy of Sen\nator Frank E. Ployhar complete files\nof both the House and Senate bills, as\nwell as journals were furnished for use\nat these meetings. These gatherings\nare very instructive and are held\nstrictly along non-party lines for the\npurpose of- general instruction and in\nformation for ^he woman voter. It is\nto be hoped that the women will con\ntinue their interest and that future\nmeetings may be largely attended.\nMuch valuable information can be\ngained.\n9\n1921 AUTO BLANKS\nRECEIVED IN V. C.\nChief of Police Swanson informs the\nTim&s-Record today that he has re\nceived a supply of auto registration\nblanks, which can be secured by call\ning at the police station, under the\nCity Hall. Registration fee blanks,\nstating the amount that must be paid\non each make of car have also been re\nceived, and-all information concerning\nthese will !be gladly given out. The\nblanks are somewhat belated, due to a\ntardy printer, but are now ready for\ndistribution.\nSchedules for 1921 are based upon\nhorsepower, weight and -the retail\nprice at the factory. For this reason\nthe schedules Represent a complex\ncomputation., For cars which have\nbeen licensed before the determining\nfactor.is the number of times the car\nhas been registered. Owners of cars\ntherefore, should be careful to ascer\ntain the exact\nrfee\nfrom the columin-\nous tables, covering several printed\npages.\nExamples of fees for registration\nfor new cars in 1921 follow:\nDodge\u2014Touting car, $13.80 road\nster, $12.95 sedan, $18.75 coupe.\n$16.90 scren, one-half ton, $15.45\npanel, one-half ton, $15.75.\nOverland and Willy-Knight\u2014Mod\nel 4-T touring, $10.05 4-R roadster,\n$9.85 4-C coupe, $12.90 4-S sedan\n$13.55 20-T, touring, $18355 20-R,\nroadster, $18.65 20-C, coupe, $22.30\n20-S sedan, $23.\nEssex\u2014Phaeton touring, $14.95\nroadster, $14.75 sedan, $19.85 cabrio\nlet, $17.70.\nFord\u2014Touring, $8 runabout, $7.55\nsedan, $10 coupelet, $9.75 one-ton\ntruck, $12.45.\nChandler\u2014Touring, $18.40 road\nster, $18.40 dispatch, $18.80 sedan,\n$24.70 coupe, $23.80 limousine.\n$26.70,\nInternational Truck\u2014Express, three\nfourths ton, $19.25 one-ton, $21.20\none and one-half ton, $25.45 two-ton.\n$31.15 three and one-half ton, $50.55\nDort\u2014Touring, $10.95 sedan, $16.15\nroadster, $11.75 coupe, $15.75.\nNash\u2014Touring 5-passenger, $16.80\n7-passenger, $17.90 sedan, $24 coupe.\n$22.50 roadster, $16.60 sport $17.80.\nOakland\u2014Touring, $13.65 raodster.\n$13.25 sedan, $17.60 coupe, $17/40.\nHnbmobile Touring, $14.90 road\nster, $14.70 coupe, $20.90 sedan.\n$21.10.\nHudson Phaeton, 4-passenger\n$21.25 phaeton, 7-passenger, $22.15\nsedan, $27.55 cabriolet, $25.15 coupe,\n$21.50 touring limousine, $28.65\nlimousine $30.75 town car, $30.55.\nStudebaker\u2014EJ touring. $14.55 se\ndan, $20.40 landau roadster, $16.80\nEG touring, $20.75 EH touring\n$17.50.\nBrack Sedan, 7-passenger, $26.60\ntouring, 7-passenger, $16.95 coupe\n$24.65 sedan, 5-passenger $24 coupe,\n1122.95 touring, 5-passenger, $17.70\nroadster, $17.50.\nBUM SCALES ARE\nFOUNDTOBEFEW\nThe old story of the merchant and\nhis short weight scales is fl'atly con\ntradicted by the findings of the scales\ninspection department of the regula\ntory division, Agricultural college at\nFargo. Of the incorrect computing\nscales discovered by the department,\nnine out of every ten weigh in favor\nof the customer, a department report\ndeclares. The percentage of incorrect\ncounter and computing scales found\nis 35.\nOf 20 latest model scales inspected\nrecently irr Fargo, 16 were found to\nbe incorrect and most of them in fa\nvor of the customer. Some of the 16\nwere as much as 14 pounds over\nweight in 500 pounds. One merchant\nin the state whose scales were found\nto be overweight estimated that the\nincorrect adjustment had lost him $40\nin the last year in sugar scales alone.\nThe Annulal loss to .each merchant over\nthe average incorrect scale is esti\nmated at $50.\nThe north city Fargo city scales\nwere found to be underweight, how\never, weighing 17 pounds short of\n1,0(K) pounds. The citizen who filled\nhis coal bin with coal at $19 a ton,\nlost $2.58 on his' eight tons of fuel.\nThe scales were adjusted .to weigh\nproperly as the result of the inspect\nion. The southside city scfeles were\nfound to be correctly adjusted.\nThe percentage of incorrect measur\ning pumps is 50 per cent, the report\n3hows, of which nine out of ten give\nshort measure, a reversal of the in\ncorrect scales figures. The average\nshortage in measuring pumps was\nfound to be approximately three per-*\ncent, or 'sufficient to make a difference\nof one^ cent a gallon in gasoline at\npresent* prices.\nVery few of the scales and measures\nhad been .tampered with, department,\nofficials say, and people as a whole'\nare anxious to have their instruments\ncorrect. Some people having expen\nsive up to date scales resent having\nchem tested, as they took especial\npains to get instruments that they\nthought were correct. The man'aiger\nof one Fargo branch house was angry\nwhen the inspector insisted upon test\ning his scales, saying that he had in\nstructed his company to send him the\nbest scales it could secure. His mood\nchanged, however, when the inspector\nshowed him the scales were over\nweighted 14 pounds in 500 pounds\nand he thanked the inspector for show\ning him why weights 6n the goods\nsent him by his house had inot been\nholding out.\nOf 120 \\Vagon scales tested between\nOctober 12 and November 12, 37 or\nor approximately 3t\u00bbper cent were in?\ncorrect, 35 'weighing slow or short\nand two weighing fast or too much.\nThe average amount of error for the\nshort weight \"Scales was seven pounds\np\u00a3r 1,000, and of the two over weight\nscalps' 7 1-2 perl,000 pounds.\nFactory experts are at work mak\ning adjustments on the counter and\ncomputing scales found incorrect. The\nscales are tested for various weights.,\nas sometimes they will weight correct\nly at one weight and incorrectly at an\n\u2022a\"r-\nSTATECONTEST\nFOR MUSICIANS\nValley City talent will have an op-'\nportunity to participate in the state\nmusical contest 'for apiateur and\nyoung professionals musicians as a\npart of the national contest under\nthe auspices of the National Federa\ntion of Music clubs, according to an\nnouncement today. It will be held\nin Grand Forks in April.\nThe Winner-of the.\nstate contest will\nbe given a prize of $25 and gains\nthe right thereby to represent North\nDakota in fhe district contest com\npeting against entrants from South\nDakota, Montana and Minnesota.\nPrizes will be given in the district\ncompetition, winners to be eligible\nto the national event to be held in\nconnection with the biennial meet\ning of the National Federation of\nMusic clubs in Davenport, Iowa\nMoline and Rock Island, 111., next\nJune.\nWinners of the national contest\nmil participate in recitals in Aeolin\nhall, New York, in Kimball hall, Chi\ncago, and in cqncert engagements\nthroughout the United States.\nFour different sections will be ar\nranged for each of the contests: fe\nmale voices, male voices, violin and\npiano.\nInformation concerning the state\nevent is in the hands of Mrs. J. A.\nJardine, Fargo, state president of the\nFederation of Music clubs, and E. Hi\nWilcox, University, N. D., chairman\nof the contest committee.\nTOPLAYHERE\nWednesday evening two fast games\nwill be played, in the ^igh school gym\nnasium. One between the. Jamestown\nfive and the Valley City first team,\nthe other between the Sanborn aggre\ngation and Mr: Scarlett's fifty-fourth\nsquad.\nBoth of these games promise to be\nfast, furious, and exciting. James\ntown defeated' Valley City earlier in\nthe season andi the Valley City boys\nhave been waiting for a chance to re\ninstate themselves. The weaknesses\nbrought to light, in. the Bismarck game\nare being carefully remedied. A de\ncided change in the lineup will be\nmade by that time.\nThe boys are at least getting on to\nthe new style of basketball, coached\nby Mr. Fagin, and1, they say that once\nthey get it, there isn't a team in the\nstate that will have a chance against\nthem.\nThe dashing, smashing fifty-fourth\nsquad, will have a hard game to play\nwhen they meet the Sanborn basket\ntossers. Their game will be played\nas a preliminary to the Jamestown\nValley City game\nThe band has again consented to be\npresent. The seating arrangements\nhave been reorganized, thus increas\ning the capacity of the gym by about\ntwo hundred. The first game starts at\n7:15 sharp.\nCUB/k\nYep, the groundhog, saw his \"shad\nder\" alright.\nJoin the Farm Bureau. Do it now.\nThe Nelson, Joe and Chas. Schieb\nfamilies, called on Geo. Vaught's Sun\nday evening and report a pleasant\ntime.\nA petition was presented to the\nschool board Thursday for the reopen\ning of the Cuba school. After due con\nconsideration the board decided to\ncomply with the request, as soon as\na teacher can be secured. In all pro\nbability this-can be done so as to com.-^\nmence school Monday, Feb. 14th.\nAlvin Schieb who is attending the\nCatholic school in Valley City was\nhome for over Sunday.\nMr. aiid Mrs. Vernon Grant enter\ntained a few friends and neighbors\nWednesday Evening.\nThe Chas. Schieb home on Main\nstreet was the scene of a jolly party\nThursday evening. Cards were the\npastime, and a sumptous luncheon was\nserved. Mr. and Mrs. Schieb are in\ndeed royal entertainers.\nGeorge Kuhry, Tony Yanish, John\nNodck and Mike Thilmony of Spring\nvale^ township were Cuba visitors\nThursday in the interest of School\nDist. 55. Come again gentlemen you\nare always welcome.\nMrs. Theodore Danielson is under\nthe care of a doctor at her home on\nNorth Lake street. Her many friends\nhofee for her speedy recovery.\nV. E. Grant was a Valley City visi\ntor Friday in the interest of the Farm\nBureau, and incidentally stayed in tot\nthe Masonic doings.\nTwo cars of hogs were shipped from\nCuba Saturday to the St. Paul mar\nket. Harry Wilkins and Lewis Sod\nman were the largest contributors to\nthis shipment and had some good\nhogs, raised on alfalfa and home\ngrown corn. These gentlemen came\nhere from Iowa, and are progressive\nfarmers and a valuable, asset to the\ncounty.\nMr. and Mrs. Carl King and *daugh\nter Elsie entertained a few friends\nSunday. There were lots of good\nthings to eat, and a general good time\nwas had.\nThe automobile show is on in the\nHair at Cuba this week, and judging\nfrom the way it starts off it. will be\nan entire success both from the stand\npoint of display, and attendance. Most\nof the entries are in place and among\nthose holding conspicuous places are\nthe Chandler Six, Chevrolet and Ford.\nAn expert is in charge and ready at\nall times to show the working p'krts\nof the different models and to answer\nany questions pertaining.to speed,\nlubrication, cooling, etc. The hall is\nvery tastily, decorated, and while this\nis the first smpt at holding a show\nit is hoped that it can be made an\nannual affair.\n'Have you seen the Auto show?\nAfter\n\u00ab*\u00bbr\n3^5\nt' '-V\nIt\niff'\n\"4\nA\nthe auto show, what next?\nMiss Elsie King spent Monday aft\nernoon with Mrs. V. E. Grant.\nIt is reported that there will be a\ncouple of weddings in Cuba Township\nin the near future.\nThe members of the Olaf Olstad\nfamily are said to be quite ill. Our\ntireless is not working so we did not\nC?t the particulars.\n\u2022acfru.-sfci'","height":"26297","width":"18295"}}
